30442/http://citynewslive.com/fullstory2k5-insight-Football+fans+sore+Zesh+Rehman-status-26-newsID-69853.html |archive-date=12 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Nathan Ellington]]{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Martial arts===\n* [[Qasim Beg]] {{spaced ndash}} undefeated kickboxing champion, two-time world champion{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* [[Imran Khan (kickboxer)|Imran Khan]] {{spaced ndash}} two-time World Muay Thai champion{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* [[Kamal Shalorus]]{{spaced ndash}} professional [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] fighter<ref>[http://www.iranian.com/main/blog/yousefi/kamal-shalorus-prince-persia-mma].</ref>\n* [[Lutalo Muhammad]] {{spaced ndash}} Taekwondo athlete\n* [[Nisar Smiler]] {{spaced ndash}} two-time karate world champion and 50-time gold medallist\n* [[Ruqsana Begum]] {{spaced ndash}} [[Muay Thai]] kickboxer; in 2010,  became the current British female Atomweight (48\u201350&nbsp;kg) Muay Thai boxing champion; in September 2012, she was nominated as captain of the British Muay Thai Team<ref name=\"thedailystarbegum\">{{cite news |last=Ahmed Ully|first=Ansar|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=250326|title=Kick-boxer Ruqsana wins bronze|location= |work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|date=19 September 2012|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Ali Jacko]] {{spaced ndash}} world champion kickboxer from east London{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* [[Riaz Amin]] {{spaced ndash}} Britain's youngest WEKAF (World Eskrima/Kali/Arnis Federation) world champion; practises [[Shotokan Karate]] and [[Filipino martial arts]]\n\n===Other===\n* [[Aadel Kardooni]]{{spaced ndash}} former [[Leicester Tigers]] and [[England Saxons|England A]] rugby player<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/england/3447882/England-are-rugbys-true-Rainbow-Nation-Rugby-Union.html].  ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.</ref>\n* [[Abdi Jama]] {{spaced ndash}} [[wheelchair basketball]] player, selected to play for [[Team GB]] in the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in London\n* [[Adam Khan]] {{spaced ndash}} racing driver from Bridlington, Yorkshire; represents Pakistan in the A1 Grand Prix series; demonstration driver for the Renault F1 racing team<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.formula1.com/news/interviews/2009/5/9417.html |title=Q&A with Renault demo driver Adam Khan |author=F1 |website= |publisher=Formula One World Championship |accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Adam Gemili]] {{spaced ndash}} sprinter of Iranian and Moroccan heritage{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n* [[Aamir Ghaffar]] \u2013 English [[badminton]] player<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/badminton/3118941/Aamir-Ghaffar-retires-from-Internationals-Badminton.html|title=Aamir Ghaffar retires from Internationals|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=October 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Bulbul Hussain]] {{spaced ndash}} wheelchair rugby player; plays mostly in a defensive role for Kent Crusaders and the [[Great Britain at the Olympics|Great Britain]] paralympic team; in 2008 and 2012, he played for Great Britain at the [[Paralympic Games]]<ref name=\"thedailystarhussain\">{{cite news |last=Ullah|first=Ansar Ahmed|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=248542|title=Bengali rugby star Bulbul eyes gold|work= The Daily Star|date=6 September 2012|accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> \n* [[Enaam Ahmed]] \u2013 British F3 racing driver, series' youngest-ever champion at 17 years old<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2015/113/road-simon-arron | title=On the road with Simon Arron &#124; Motor Sport Magazine Archive| date=2015-09-23}}</ref>\n* [[Gaz Choudhry]] {{spaced ndash}} [[wheelchair basketball]] player who was selected to play for [[British Paralympic Association|Paralympics GB]] in the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in London<ref name=\"GB Paralympics\">{{cite web|url=