\n| mouth              = [[Saint Lawrence River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], MRC [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.040051|-70.883446|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|6|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|1077|km2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   =(upward from the mouth) [[rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]], ruisseau Clair, Le Big Creek, d\u00e9charge des lacs Auguste et Eug\u00e8ne, ruisseau Noir, d\u00e9charge d'un ensemble de lacs dont lac du Li\u00e8vre, lac Bouchard lac Croche et lac \u00e0 l'Ours, d\u00e9charge du lac Thibault...\n| tributaries_right  =(upward from the mouth) [[Jean-Larose River]], ruisseau non identifi\u00e9, ruisseau non identifi\u00e9, [[rivi\u00e8re du Moulin (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]], [[rivi\u00e8re des Roches (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]], ruisseau non identifi\u00e9,  ruisseau non identifi\u00e9, d\u00e9charge de deux lacs non identifi\u00e9s, [[rivi\u00e8re du Mont Saint-\u00c9tienne]], [[Br\u00fbl\u00e9e River (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]], ruisseau Beaumier, ruisseau Lalibert\u00e9, d\u00e9charge du lac Saint-Louis, [[Petite rivi\u00e8re Savane]], d\u00e9charge d'un ensemble de lacs dont Lac de la Ligne de Comt\u00e9, lac du Nord-Est et lac Henri-B\u00e9ique, [[rivi\u00e8re Savane du Nord]]...\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n[[File:Canyon Sainte-Anne by Amerune.jpg|thumb|right|[[Canyon Sainte-Anne]] on Sainte-Anne-du-Nord River]]\n\n'''Ste-Anne-du-Nord River''' is a tributary of the northwest shore of the [[Saint Lawrence river]] where it flows at the height of [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]]. This river flows in [[Capitale-Nationale]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]. The river passes through [[Canyon Sainte-Anne]] before joining the [[Saint Lawrence River]] at [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]].\n\n== Geography ==\nRivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne is a river in the [[Capitale-Nationale]] region. It has a length of 72,2 km, covers a basin of {{convert|1077|km2|abbr=on}} and has an average flow of 26 m3/s. The river finds its source at Lac de la Tour in [[Grands-Jardins National Park]]. From there, it flows south and ends at [[Beaupr\u00e9, Qu\u00e9bec|Beaupr\u00e9]], opposite [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]], 35 km northeast of the city of [[Qu\u00e9bec (city)|Quebec]] in the [[St. Lawrence River]]<ref>[http://www.charlevoixmontmorency.ca/nouvelles/index.php?pages/Comit%C3%A9-de-la-rivi%C3%A8re-Sainte-Anne-du-Nord Sainte-Anne-du-Nord River Committee]</ref>.\n\nIn [[Saint-Ferr\u00e9ol-les-Neiges]] are the ''Seven Chutes'', [[waterfall|fall]]s which in many cases are 128 m high<ref>[http://www.liquidlore.com/quebec/7chutes/7chutes.html Sept Chutes]</ref>. Then the river crosses the [[Canyon Sainte-Anne]], a [[Canyon|gorge]] with a length of 10 km. At its end, in [[Saint-Joachim, Quebec|Saint-Joachim]] is the Sainte-Anne waterfall, 74 m high.\n\n'''Upper course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream of Lac de la Tour)''' (segment of {{convert|9.0|km}})\n\n* {{convert|3.4|km}} towards the south-east, branching east towards the end of the segment by crossing a first small lake, crossing the [[Quebec Route 381|route 381]], then crossing the Lake at Liz\u00e9 (length: {{convert|0.6|km}}; altitude: {{convert|792|m}}), to its mouth;\n* {{convert|5.6|km}} towards the southwest crossing on {{convert|0.6|km}} Lake Perrault, then crossing on {{convert|1.5|km}} on [[Lac Sainte-Anne du Nord]] (altitude: {{convert|748|km}}), to its mouth;\n\n'''Upper course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream from Lac Sainte-Anne du Nord)''' (segment of {{convert|9.3|km}})\n\n* {{convert|0.9|km}} towards the southwest in a deep valley by collecting the discharge (coming from the east) of the Pointu Lake and the discharge (coming from the northwest) of the Lac du Versant, to the outlet (coming from the north) from Lac \u00e0 Poux;\n* {{convert|0.5|km}} south, to the outlet (coming from the southwest) from Lac Turgeon;\n* {{convert|1.9|km}} to the southeast, crossing Lake Arthabaska (length: {{convert|0.2|km}}; altitude: {{convert|701|m}}), crossing Pemmican Lake (length: {{convert|0.4|km}}; altitude: {{convert|698|m}}), up to Wabano Dam;\n* {{convert|2.8|km}} south-east almost in a straight line, crossing Lac Trou\u00e9 and Lac Long, crossing the Barrage du Lac-Long, collecting the discharge (coming from the north ) from Buies and Th\u00e9odule lakes, to a bend in the river; then south in a deep valley curving east to the outlet (coming from the northwest) of Chaudi\u00e8re and Beaupr\u00e9 lakes;\n* {{convert|1.8|km}} to the south in a deep valley, collecting the Courganne stream (coming from the west), to the Petit Lac Double stream (coming from the northeast);\n* {{convert|1.4|km}} to the south in a deep valley, collecting a river (coming from the west), bending towards the southeast, until the confluence of the [[rivi\u00e8re Savane du Nord]] (coming from the south);\n\n'''Intermediate course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream of the \u201crivi\u00e8re Savane du Nord)''' (segment of {{convert|26.4|km}})\n\n* {{convert|5.0|km}} towards the south-east in a deep valley, collecting the discharge (coming from the west) from the North-East Lake, until Le Big Creek (coming from the north);\n* {{convert|8.3|km}} towards the south-east in a deep valley, then towards the east, up to a bend of the river corresponding to a stream (coming from the north-east);\n* {{convert|3.7|km}} to the south, forming a gap towards the east at the start of the segment, then crossing eight series of rapids, up to [[Petite rivi\u00e8re Savane]] (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|4.5|km}} to the south, forming a large S at the start of the segment, crossing five series of rapids, to the outlet (coming from the east) of an unidentified lake;\n* {{convert|4.9|km}} to the south by crossing several series of rapids, by collecting the Beaumier stream (coming from the northwest), bypassing two islands, up to a bend of the river, corresponding to the confluence of the [[Br\u00fbl\u00e9e River (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]] (coming from the south);\n\n'''Intermediate course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9e River)''' (segment of {{convert|16.5|km}})\n\n* {{convert|4.4|km}} towards the south-east by forming a large S, bypassing a first island (length: {{convert|0.3|km}}) and a second island (length: {{convert|0.5|km}}), to the confluence of the Sables Mountain Creek (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|1.8|km}} first towards the east by collecting the discharge (coming from the north) of an unidentified lake, towards the south, then the south-east, crossing series of rapids, to the [[Mont Saint-\u00c9tienne River]] (coming from the west);\n* {{convert|2.1|km}} towards the south-east by crossing a series of rapids at the start of the segment, up to the [[Quebec Route 360|route 360]] bridge;\n* {{convert|5.2|km}} south-east, south, then south-east, collecting a stream (coming from the north-west), relatively in a straight line, up to the [[Lombrette River]] (from the northeast);\n* {{convert|1.4|km}} southwards, bending westwards, to the Sept-Chutes dam;\n* {{convert|1.6|km}} towards the south-west by crossing the seven falls (in front of the hamlet \"Les Sept-Chutes\") and a series of rapids, until the [[rivi\u00e8re des Roches (Sainte-Anne River tributary)|rivi\u00e8re des Roches]] (coming from the north);\n\n'''Lower course of the Sainte-Anne river''' (segment of {{convert|11.0|km}})\n\n* {{convert|5.6|km}} to the south in a deep valley and crossing several series of rapids, forming a hook towards the east, crossing the Bassin de l'\u00c9rabli\u00e8re in mid-segment where it receives a stream (coming from the west), then forming a large curve towards the west, up to the Sainte-Anne Falls corresponding to the confluence of the [[river du Moulin (Sainte-Anne River)|rivi\u00e8re du Moulin]] (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|2.4|km}} to the south, forming a large S to bypass the mountains, crossing two series of rapids and collecting the waters of the [[Jean-Larose River]] at the end of the segment (coming from the northwest), to a dam;\n* {{convert|1.4|km}} towards the south-east by forming a curve towards the north-east, crossing three series of rapids, up to the bridge of the [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]];\n* {{convert|1.1|km}} first towards the east, then towards the south bypassing the urban sector of [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], up to the railway bridge;\n* {{convert|0.5|km}} towards the south-east by crossing the bay endowed with a marina which serves as a haven for pleasure boats, to its mouth.<ref name=Atlas>[https://atlas.gc.ca/toporama/fr/index.html Atlas du Canada - Minist\u00e8re des ressources naturelles du Canada - Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne - Mesures de distances et d'altitude \u00e9tablis \u00e0 partir de l'application des mesures du site.]</ref>.\n\nThe Sainte-Anne river ends at [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], opposite the northern tip of [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]], on the northwest shore of the [[Saint Lawrence river]]. This mouth is located at:\n* 35 km northeast of downtown of the city of [[Quebec (city)|Quebec]]<ref>[http://www.charlevoixmontmorency.ca/nouvelles/index.php?pages/Comit%C3 % A9-de-la-rivi% C3% A8re-Sainte-Anne-du-Nord Sainte-Anne-du-Nord River Committee]</ref>;\n* {{convert|26.0|km}} north-east of the bridge connecting the [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]] to [[L'Ange-Gardien, Quebec|L'Ange-Gardien]] (C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9);\n* {{convert|2.5|km}} north-west of [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]], crossing the [[Channel of \u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]].\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe toponym \"Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne\" was formalized on April 4, 1982 at the Place Names Bank of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec<ref name=\"CTQ\">[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/toposweb/Fiche.aspx?no_seq=109029 - Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne].</ref>\n\n== Sept-Chutes hydroelectric plant ==\nThe [[Sept-Chutes power plant]], a [[Hydroelectric power|hydroelectric power plant]] ''[[Run-of-the-river power plant|run-of-the-water power plant]]'' belonging to [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]] is on the Sainte-Anne river. It was built in 1916 and modernized in 1999. It has 4 turbines for a total output of 22 MW. The hydraulic potential amounts to 124.97 m. The power station can be visited<ref>[http://www.hydroquebec.com/production/centrale-hydroelectrique.html Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec: Hydroelectric power stations]</ref>.\n{|align=center\n|[[Image:Canyon Sainte-Anne by Amerune.jpg|thumb|300px|<center>[[Canyon Sainte-Anne]]</center>]]\n|}\n== Hydro-Canyon hydroelectric plant ==\nIt was in 2016 that the hydroelectric power station of [http://www.hydro-canyon.com/ Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Hydro-Canyon Saint-Joachim] started up a [[Hydroelectric power|hydroelectric power station]] ''[[ Central over water | over water]] 300 meters upstream from [[Canyon Sainte-Anne]].''\n\nThe Hydro-Canyon Saint-Joachim run-of-river power plant project was designed taking into account the technical and environmental aspects of the integration environment.\n\nThe development will harmonize with the recreotourism facilities of Canyon Sainte-Anne.\n\nThe works will optimize the site on the hydroelectric level while developing the potential of the Sainte-Anne waterfall. The maximum power of the plant will be 23.2 MW.\n\nThe installation will include:\n* A weir threshold to maintain the upstream level of the river\n* A spillway\n* A water intake\n* An entrance gallery\n* A power plant including production equipment\n* A substation and a power line connecting the site to the Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec network\n\n== Sport ==\n[[File:Kayak Tandem.jpg|thumbnail]]\nThe Sainte-Anne-du-Nord river has also been used since 1966 by a club and a [[river kayak]] school. First bearing the name of Club Echohamok, it has evolved to bear today the name of [http://www.kayakbeaupre.com/Kayak C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9]. It must be said that the Sainte-Anne-du-Nord river has a portion of river located between the Sept-Chutes hydroelectric plant and the Hydro-Canyon hydroelectric plant which is classified 5 stars by the guide of rivers of Quebec.\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Appendices ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n\n=== See also ===\n*[[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n*[[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pikauba]], un territoire non organis\u00e9\n*[[Saint-Ferr\u00e9ol-les-Neiges]], une municipalit\u00e9\n*[[Saint-Joachim, Quebec|Saint-Joachim]], une municipalit\u00e9\n*[[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec]], une municipalit\u00e9\n*[[Chenal de l'\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]]\n*[[Parc national des Grands-Jardins]]\n*[[Laurentides Wildlife Reserve]]\n*[[Canyon Sainte-Anne]]\n*[[St. Lawrence River]]\n*[[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{Portal|Capitale-Nationale|lakes and streams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sainte-Anne-Du-Nord River}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the Saint Lawrence River]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|river which joins the St. Lawrence at Beaupr\u00e9|river which joins the St. Lawrence at Ste-Anne-de-la-P\u00e9rade|Sainte-Anne River}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Sainte-Anne River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = ''Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne-du-Nord''\n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Saint-Anne-du-Nord River.jpg\n| image_caption      = Sainte-Anne (Beaupr\u00e9) River\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Quebec]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Capitale-Nationale]]\n| subdivision_type4  = Regional County Municipality\n| subdivision_name4  = [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]] and [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type5  = Municipalities\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pikauba]] TNO, [[Baie-Saint-Paul]], [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]], [[Saint-Ferr\u00e9ol-les-Neiges]] et [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|97|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Lac Sainte-Anne-du-Nord\n| source1_location   = [[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pikauba]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|47.685499|-70.736332|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|914|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[Saint Lawrence River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], MRC [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.040051|-70.883446|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|6|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|1077|km2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   =(upward from the mouth) [[rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]], ruisseau Clair, Le Big Creek, d\u00e9charge des lacs Auguste et Eug\u00e8ne, ruisseau Noir, d\u00e9charge d'un ensemble de lacs dont lac du Li\u00e8vre, lac Bouchard lac Croche et lac \u00e0 l'Ours, d\u00e9charge du lac Thibault...\n| tributaries_right  =(upward from the mouth) [[Jean-Larose River]], ruisseau non identifi\u00e9, ruisseau non identifi\u00e9, [[rivi\u00e8re du Moulin (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]], [[rivi\u00e8re des Roches (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]], ruisseau non identifi\u00e9,  ruisseau non identifi\u00e9, d\u00e9charge de deux lacs non identifi\u00e9s, [[rivi\u00e8re du Mont Saint-\u00c9tienne]], [[Br\u00fbl\u00e9e River (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]], ruisseau Beaumier, ruisseau Lalibert\u00e9, d\u00e9charge du lac Saint-Louis, [[Petite rivi\u00e8re Savane]], d\u00e9charge d'un ensemble de lacs dont Lac de la Ligne de Comt\u00e9, lac du Nord-Est et lac Henri-B\u00e9ique, [[rivi\u00e8re Savane du Nord]]...\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n[[File:Canyon Sainte-Anne by Amerune.jpg|thumb|right|[[Canyon Sainte-Anne]] on Sainte-Anne-du-Nord River]]\n\n'''Ste-Anne-du-Nord River''' is a tributary of the northwest shore of the [[Saint Lawrence river]] where it flows at the height of [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]]. This river flows in [[Capitale-Nationale]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]. The river passes through [[Canyon Sainte-Anne]] before joining the [[Saint Lawrence River]] at [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]].\n\n== Geography ==\nRivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne is a river in the [[Capitale-Nationale]] region. It has a length of 72,2 km, covers a basin of {{convert|1077|km2|abbr=on}} and has an average flow of 26 m3/s. The river finds its source at Lac de la Tour in [[Grands-Jardins National Park]]. From there, it flows south and ends at [[Beaupr\u00e9, Qu\u00e9bec|Beaupr\u00e9]], opposite [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]], 35 km northeast of the city of [[Qu\u00e9bec (city)|Quebec]] in the [[St. Lawrence River]]<ref>[http://www.charlevoixmontmorency.ca/nouvelles/index.php?pages/Comit%C3%A9-de-la-rivi%C3%A8re-Sainte-Anne-du-Nord Sainte-Anne-du-Nord River Committee]</ref>.\n\nIn [[Saint-Ferr\u00e9ol-les-Neiges]] are the ''Seven Chutes'', [[waterfall|fall]]s which in many cases are 128 m high<ref>[http://www.liquidlore.com/quebec/7chutes/7chutes.html Sept Chutes]</ref>. Then the river crosses the [[Canyon Sainte-Anne]], a [[Canyon|gorge]] with a length of 10 km. At its end, in [[Saint-Joachim, Quebec|Saint-Joachim]] is the Sainte-Anne waterfall, 74 m high.\n\n'''Upper course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream of Lac de la Tour)''' (segment of {{convert|9.0|km}})\n\n* {{convert|3.4|km}} towards the south-east, branching east towards the end of the segment by crossing a first small lake, crossing the [[route 381 (Quebec) | route 381]], then crossing the Lake at Liz\u00e9 (length: {{convert|0.6|km}}; altitude: {{convert|792|m}}), to its mouth;\n* {{convert|5.6|km}} towards the southwest crossing on {{convert|0.6|km}} Lake Perrault, then crossing on {{convert|1.5|km}} on [[Lac Sainte-Anne du Nord]] (altitude: {{convert|748|km}}), to its mouth;\n\n'''Upper course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream from Lac Sainte-Anne du Nord)''' (segment of {{convert|9.3|km}})\n\n* {{convert|0.9|km}} towards the southwest in a deep valley by collecting the discharge (coming from the east) of the Pointu Lake and the discharge (coming from the northwest) of the Lac du Versant, to the outlet (coming from the north) from Lac \u00e0 Poux;\n* {{convert|0.5|km}} south, to the outlet (coming from the southwest) from Lac Turgeon;\n* {{convert|1.9|km}} to the southeast, crossing Lake Arthabaska (length: {{convert|0.2|km}}; altitude: {{convert|701|m}}), crossing Pemmican Lake (length: {{convert|0.4|km}}; altitude: {{convert|698|m}}), up to Wabano Dam;\n* {{convert|2.8|km}} south-east almost in a straight line, crossing Lac Trou\u00e9 and Lac Long, crossing the Barrage du Lac-Long, collecting the discharge (coming from the north ) from Buies and Th\u00e9odule lakes, to a bend in the river; then south in a deep valley curving east to the outlet (coming from the northwest) of Chaudi\u00e8re and Beaupr\u00e9 lakes;\n* {{convert|1.8|km}} to the south in a deep valley, collecting the Courganne stream (coming from the west), to the Petit Lac Double stream (coming from the northeast);\n* {{convert|1.4|km}} to the south in a deep valley, collecting a river (coming from the west), bending towards the southeast, until the confluence of the [[rivi\u00e8re Savane du Nord]] (coming from the south);\n\n'''Intermediate course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream of the \u201crivi\u00e8re Savane du Nord)''' (segment of {{convert|26.4|km}})\n\n* {{convert|5.0|km}} towards the south-east in a deep valley, collecting the discharge (coming from the west) from the North-East Lake, until Le Big Creek (coming from the north);\n* {{convert|8.3|km}} towards the south-east in a deep valley, then towards the east, up to a bend of the river corresponding to a stream (coming from the north-east);\n* {{convert|3.7|km}} to the south, forming a gap towards the east at the start of the segment, then crossing eight series of rapids, up to [[Petite rivi\u00e8re Savane]] (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|4.5|km}} to the south, forming a large S at the start of the segment, crossing five series of rapids, to the outlet (coming from the east) of an unidentified lake;\n* {{convert|4.9|km}} to the south by crossing several series of rapids, by collecting the Beaumier stream (coming from the northwest), bypassing two islands, up to a bend of the river, corresponding to the confluence of the [[Br\u00fbl\u00e9e River (Sainte-Anne River tributary)]] (coming from the south);\n\n'''Intermediate course of the Sainte-Anne river (downstream of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9e River)''' (segment of {{convert|16.5|km}})\n\n* {{convert|4.4|km}} towards the south-east by forming a large S, bypassing a first island (length: {{convert|0.3|km}}) and a second island (length: {{convert|0.5|km}}), to the confluence of the Sables Mountain Creek (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|1.8|km}} first towards the east by collecting the discharge (coming from the north) of an unidentified lake, towards the south, then the south-east, crossing series of rapids, to the [[Mont Saint-\u00c9tienne River]] (coming from the west);\n* {{convert|2.1|km}} towards the south-east by crossing a series of rapids at the start of the segment, up to the [[Quebec Route 360|route 360]] bridge;\n* {{convert|5.2|km}} south-east, south, then south-east, collecting a stream (coming from the north-west), relatively in a straight line, up to the [[Lombrette River]] (from the northeast);\n* {{convert|1.4|km}} southwards, bending westwards, to the Sept-Chutes dam;\n* {{convert|1.6|km}} towards the south-west by crossing the seven falls (in front of the hamlet \"Les Sept-Chutes\") and a series of rapids, until the [[rivi\u00e8re des Roches (Sainte-Anne River tributary)|rivi\u00e8re des Roches]] (coming from the north);\n\n'''Lower course of the Sainte-Anne river''' (segment of {{convert|11.0|km}})\n\n* {{convert|5.6|km}} to the south in a deep valley and crossing several series of rapids, forming a hook towards the east, crossing the Bassin de l'\u00c9rabli\u00e8re in mid-segment where it receives a stream (coming from the west), then forming a large curve towards the west, up to the Sainte-Anne Falls corresponding to the confluence of the [[river du Moulin (Sainte-Anne River)|rivi\u00e8re du Moulin]] (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|2.4|km}} to the south, forming a large S to bypass the mountains, crossing two series of rapids and collecting the waters of the [[Jean-Larose River]] at the end of the segment (coming from the northwest), to a dam;\n* {{convert|1.4|km}} towards the south-east by forming a curve towards the north-east, crossing three series of rapids, up to the bridge of the [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]];\n* {{convert|1.1|km}} first towards the east, then towards the south bypassing the urban sector of [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], up to the railway bridge;\n* {{convert|0.5|km}} towards the south-east by crossing the bay endowed with a marina which serves as a haven for pleasure boats, to its mouth.<ref name=Atlas>[https://atlas.gc.ca/toporama/fr/index.html Atlas du Canada - Minist\u00e8re des ressources naturelles du Canada - Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne - Mesures de distances et d'altitude \u00e9tablis \u00e0 partir de l'application des mesures du site.]</ref>.\n\nThe Sainte-Anne river ends at [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], opposite the northern tip of [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]], on the northwest shore of the [[Saint Lawrence river]]. This mouth is located at:\n* 35 km northeast of downtown of the city of [[Quebec (city)|Quebec]]<ref>[http://www.charlevoixmontmorency.ca/nouvelles/index.php?pages/Comit%C3 % A9-de-la-rivi% C3% A8re-Sainte-Anne-du-Nord Sainte-Anne-du-Nord River Committee]</ref>;\n* {{convert|26.0|km}} north-east of the bridge connecting the [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]] to [[L'Ange-Gardien, Quebec|L'Ange-Gardien]] (C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9);\n* {{convert|2.5|km}} north-west of [[\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]], crossing the [[Channel of \u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]].\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe toponym \"Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne\" was formalized on April 4, 1982 at the Place Names Bank of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec<ref name=\"CTQ\">[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/toposweb/Fiche.aspx?no_seq=109029 - Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Rivi\u00e8re Sainte-Anne].</ref>\n\n== Sept-Chutes hydroelectric plant ==\nThe [[Sept-Chutes power plant]], a [[Hydroelectric power|hydroelectric power plant]] ''[[Run-of-the-river power plant|run-of-the-water power plant]]'' belonging to [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]] is on the Sainte-Anne river. It was built in 1916 and modernized in 1999. It has 4 turbines for a total output of 22 MW. The hydraulic potential amounts to 124.97 m. The power station can be visited<ref>[http://www.hydroquebec.com/production/centrale-hydroelectrique.html Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec: Hydroelectric power stations]</ref>.\n{|align=center\n|[[Image:Canyon Sainte-Anne by Amerune.jpg|thumb|300px|<center>[[Canyon Sainte-Anne]]</center>]]\n|}\n== Hydro-Canyon hydroelectric plant ==\nIt was in 2016 that the hydroelectric power station of [http://www.hydro-canyon.com/ Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Hydro-Canyon Saint-Joachim] started up a [[Hydroelectric power|hydroelectric power station]] ''[[ Central over water | over water]] 300 meters upstream from [[Canyon Sainte-Anne]].''\n\nThe Hydro-Canyon Saint-Joachim run-of-river power plant project was designed taking into account the technical and environmental aspects of the integration environment.\n\nThe development will harmonize with the recreotourism facilities of Canyon Sainte-Anne.\n\nThe works will optimize the site on the hydroelectric level while developing the potential of the Sainte-Anne waterfall. The maximum power of the plant will be 23.2 MW.\n\nThe installation will include:\n* A weir threshold to maintain the upstream level of the river\n* A spillway\n* A water intake\n* An entrance gallery\n* A power plant including production equipment\n* A substation and a power line connecting the site to the Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec network\n\n== Sport ==\n[[File:Kayak Tandem.jpg|thumbnail]]\nThe Sainte-Anne-du-Nord river has also been used since 1966 by a club and a [[river kayak]] school. First bearing the name of Club Echohamok, it has evolved to bear today the name of [http://www.kayakbeaupre.com/Kayak C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9]. It must be said that the Sainte-Anne-du-Nord river has a portion of river located between the Sept-Chutes hydroelectric plant and the Hydro-Canyon hydroelectric plant which is classified 5 stars by the guide of rivers of Quebec.\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Appendices ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n\n=== See also ===\n*[[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n*[[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pikauba]], un territoire non organis\u00e9\n*[[Saint-Ferr\u00e9ol-les-Neiges]], une municipalit\u00e9\n*[[Saint-Joachim, Quebec|Saint-Joachim]], une municipalit\u00e9\n*[[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec]], une municipalit\u00e9\n*[[Chenal de l'\u00cele d'Orl\u00e9ans]]\n*[[Parc national des Grands-Jardins]]\n*[[Laurentides Wildlife Reserve]]\n*[[Canyon Sainte-Anne]]\n*[[St. Lawrence River]]\n*[[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{Portal|Capitale-Nationale|lakes and streams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sainte-Anne-Du-Nord River}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the Saint Lawrence River]]\n", "name_user": "Veillg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sainte-Anne_River_(Beaupr%C3%A9)"}
{"title_page": "Mir iskusstva", "text_new": "{{short description|early 20th-century Russian art movement with magazine of the same name}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[File:Mir iskusstva group by B.Kustodiev (1916-20, Russian museum).jpg|thumb|350px|\"Members of the ''World of Art'' Movement\", by [[Boris Kustodiev]] (1916-1920). From left to right: [[Igor Grabar]], [[Nicholas Roerich]], [[Eugene Lanceray]], Kustodiev, [[Ivan Bilibin]], [[Anna Ostroumova-Lebedeva]], [[Alexandre Benois]], [[Heorhiy Narbut]], [[Kuzma Petrov-Vodkin]], [[Nikolay Milioti]], [[Konstantin Somov]] and [[Mstislav Dobuzhinsky]]]]\n'''''Mir iskusstva''''' ({{lang-rus|\u00ab\u041c\u0438\u0440 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u00bb|p=\u02c8m\u02b2ir \u026a\u02c8skustv\u0259}}, ''World of Art'') was a [[Russia]]n [[magazine]] and the artistic movement it inspired and embodied, which was a major influence on the Russians who helped revolutionize European art during the first decade of the 20th century. In fact, few Europeans outside Russia actually saw issues of the magazine itself.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nFrom 1909, several of the ''miriskusniki'' (i.e., members of the movement) also participated in productions of [[Sergei Diaghilev|Sergei Diaghilev's]] [[Ballets Russes]] company based in [[Paris]].\n\n==Foundation==\nThe artistic group was founded in November 1898 by a group of students that included [[Alexandre Benois]], [[Konstantin Somov]], [[Dmitry Filosofov]], [[L\u00e9on Bakst]], and [[Eugene Lansere]].<ref name=Scholl>{{cite book|last=Scholl|first=Tim|title=From Petipa to Balanchine: classical revival and the modernization of ballet|year=1994|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0415092221|pages=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4PY4YfJUWdkC&pg=PA66&dq=Mir+iskusstva+Alexandre+Benois&hl=cs&sa=X&ei=PtNfT4eHDsfoObrN7PcH&ved=0CFsQuwUwBg#v=onepage&q=Mir%20iskusstva%20Alexandre%20Benois&f=false}}</ref> The starting moments for the new artistic group was organization of the ''Exhibition of Russian and Finnish Artists'' in the [[Stieglitz Museum of Applied Arts]] in [[Saint-Petersburg]].\n\nThe magazine was co-founded in 1899 in [[Saint Petersburg|St.&nbsp;Petersburg]] by Alexandre Benois, L\u00e9on Bakst, and [[Sergei Diaghilev]] (the Chief Editor). They aimed at assailing artistic standards of the obsolescent [[Peredvizhniki]] school and promoting artistic individualism and other principles of [[Art Nouveau]]. The theoretical declarations of the art movements were stated in Diaghilev's articles \"Difficult Questions\", \"Our Imaginary Degradation\", \"Permanent Struggle\", \"In Search of Beauty\", and \"The Fundamentals of Artistic Appreciation\" published in the N1/2 and N3/4 of the new journal.\n\n==Classical period==\n[[File:Mir.iskusstwa.1899.jpg|thumb|''Mir iskusstwa'' cover 1899 by [[Maria Yakunchikova]]]]\nIn its \"classical period\" (1898-1904) the art group organized six exhibitions: 1899 (International), 1900, 1901 (At the [[Imperial Academy of Arts]], Saint Petersburg), 1902 ([[Moscow]] and Saint Petersburg), 1903, 1906 (Saint Petersburg). The sixth exhibition was seen as a Diaghilev's attempt to prevent the separation from the Moscow members of the group who organized a separate \"Exhibition of 36 artists\" (1901) and later \"The Union of Russian Artists\" group (from 1903).<ref name=Pyman>{{cite book|last=Pyman|first=Avril|title=A History of Russian Symbolism|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0521241987|pages=121|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fF4pwE4LAygC&pg=PA121&dq=Mir+iskusstva+exhibitions&hl=cs&sa=X&ei=GtRfT_H0HcSVOqXblf4H&ved=0CFEQuwUwBA#v=onepage&q=Mir%20iskusstva%20exhibitions&f=false}}</ref> The magazine ended in 1904.<ref name=Pyman/>\n\nIn 1904-1910, ''Mir iskusstva'' did not exist as a separate artistic group. Its place was inherited by the Union of Russian Artists which continued officially until 1910 and unofficially until 1924. The Union included painters ([[Valentin Serov]], [[Konstantin Korovin]], [[Boris Kustodiev]], [[Zinaida Serebriakova]], [[Sergei Lednev-Schukin]]), illustrators ([[Ivan Bilibin]], [[Konstantin Somov]], [[Dmitry Mitrohin]]), restorators ([[Igor Grabar]]), and scenic designers ([[Nicholas Roerich]], [[Serge Sudeikin]]).\n\nIn 1910 Benois published a critical article in the magazine ''Rech'''  about the Union of Russian Artists. ''Mir iskusstva'' was recreated. [[Nicholas Roerich]] became the new chairman. The group admitted new members including [[Nathan Altman]], [[Vladimir Tatlin]], and [[Martiros Saryan]]. Some said that the inclusion of [[Russian avant-garde]] painters demonstrated that the group had become an exhibition organization rather than an art movement.  In 1917 the chairman of the group became [[Ivan Bilibin]].  The same year most members of the [[Jack of Diamonds (artists)|Jack of Diamonds]] entered the group.\n\nThe group organized numerous exhibitions: 1911, 1912, 1913, 1915, 1916, 1917, 1918, 1921, 1922 Saint-Petersburg, Moscow). The last exhibition of ''Mir iskusstva'' was organized in [[Paris]] in 1927. Some members of the group entered the ''[[Zhar-Tsvet]]'' (Moscow, organized in 1924) and ''[[Four Arts]]'' (Moscow-Leningrad, organized in 1925) artistic movements.\n\n==Art==\n[[Image:Dadon shemakha.jpg|thumb|right|Ivan Bilibin's illustration to ''[[The Tale of the Golden Cockerel]]''.]]\nLike the English [[Pre-Raphaelite]]s before them, Benois and his friends were disgusted with anti-aesthetic nature of modern [[industrial society]] and sought to consolidate all [[Neo-romanticism|Neo-Romantic]] Russian artists under the banner of fighting [[Positivism]] in art.\n\nLike the Romantics before them, the ''miriskusniki'' promoted understanding and conservation of the art of previous epochs, particularly traditional [[folk art]] and the 18th-century [[rococo]]. [[Antoine Watteau]] was probably the single artist whom they admired the most.\n\nSuch Revivalist projects were treated by the ''miriskusniki'' [[humor]]ously, in a spirit of self-[[parody]].  They were fascinated with [[mask]]s and [[marionette]]s, with [[Carnival|carnaval]] and [[puppet theater]], with [[dream]]s and [[fairy-tale]]s.  Everything [[grotesque]] and playful appealed to them more than the serious and emotional.  Their favorite city was [[Venice]], so much so that [[Diaghilev]] and [[Igor Stravinsky|Stravinsky]] selected it as the place of their burial.\n\nAs for media, the ''miriskusniki'' preferred the light, airy effects of [[watercolor painting|watercolor]] and [[gouache]] to full-scale oil paintings. Seeking to bring art into every house, they often designed [[Interior design|interiors]] and [[book]]s. Bakst and Benois revolutionized [[theatrical design]] with their ground-breaking decor for ''[[Cl\u00e9op\u00e2tre]]'' (1909), ''Carnaval'' (1910), ''[[Petrushka (ballet)|Petrushka]]'' (1911), and ''[[Afternoon of a Faun (Nijinsky)|L'apr\u00e8s-midi d'un faune]]'' (1912).\nApart from three founding fathers, active members of the ''World of Art'' included [[Mstislav Dobuzhinsky]], [[Eugene Lansere]], and [[Konstantin Somov]].  Exhibitions organized by the ''World of Art'' attracted many illustrious painters from Russia and abroad, notably [[Mikhail Vrubel]], [[Mikhail Nesterov]], and [[Isaac Levitan]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200px\" caption=\"Representative works\">\nFile:Bakst Uzhin.jpg|[[Leon Bakst]]\nFile:Dobuzhinsky City Types (City Grimaces) .jpg|[[Mstislav Dobuzhinsky]]\nFile:Nemetskaya.jpg|[[Alexandre Benois]]\nFile:Eliabeth lanceret.jpg|[[Eugene Lanceray]]\nFile:1911 Somov Liebesbrief anagoria.JPG|[[Konstantin Somov]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\nHanna Chuchvaha, ''Art Periodical Culture in Late Imperial Russia (1898-1917). Print Modernism in Transition'' (Boston & Leiden: Brill, 2016) \n\n{{Russian art movements}}\n\n[[Category:1898 establishments in the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Russian symbolism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|early 20th-century Russian art movement with magazine of the same name}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[File:Mir iskusstva group by B.Kustodiev (1916-20, Russian museum).jpg|thumb|350px|\"Members of the ''World of Art'' Movement\", by [[Boris Kustodiev]] (1916-1920). From left to right: [[Igor Grabar]], [[Nicholas Roerich]], [[Eugene Lanceray]], Kustodiev, [[Ivan Bilibin]], [[Anna Ostroumova-Lebedeva]], [[Alexandre Benois]], [[Heorhiy Narbut]], [[Kuzma Petrov-Vodkin]], [[Nikolay Milioti]], [[Konstantin Somov]] and [[Mstislav Dobuzhinsky]]]]\n'''''Mir iskusstva''''' ({{lang-rus|\u00ab\u041c\u0438\u0440 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u00bb|p=\u02c8m\u02b2ir \u026a\u02c8skustv\u0259}}, ''World of Art'') was a [[Russia]]n [[magazine]] and the artistic movement it inspired and embodied, which was a major influence on the Russians who helped revolutionize European art during the first decade of the 20th century. In fact, few Europeans outside Russia actually saw issues of the magazine itself.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nFrom 1909, several of the ''miriskusniki'' (i.e., members of the movement) also participated in productions of [[Sergei Diaghilev|Sergei Diaghilev's]] [[Ballets Russes]] company based in [[Paris]].\n\n==Foundation==\nThe artistic group was founded in November 1898 by a group of students that included [[Alexandre Benois]], [[Konstantin Somov]], [[Dmitry Filosofov]], [[L\u00e9on Bakst]], and [[Eugene Lansere]].<ref name=Scholl>{{cite book|last=Scholl|first=Tim|title=From Petipa to Balanchine: classical revival and the modernization of ballet|year=1994|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0415092221|pages=66|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4PY4YfJUWdkC&pg=PA66&dq=Mir+iskusstva+Alexandre+Benois&hl=cs&sa=X&ei=PtNfT4eHDsfoObrN7PcH&ved=0CFsQuwUwBg#v=onepage&q=Mir%20iskusstva%20Alexandre%20Benois&f=false}}</ref> The starting moments for the new artistic group was organization of the ''Exhibition of Russian and Finnish Artists'' in the [[Stieglitz Museum of Applied Arts]] in [[Saint-Petersburg]].\n\nThe magazine was co-founded in 1899 in [[Saint Petersburg|St.&nbsp;Petersburg]] by Alexandre Benois, L\u00e9on Bakst, and [[Sergei Diaghilev]] (the Chief Editor). They aimed at assailing artistic standards of the obsolescent [[Peredvizhniki]] school and promoting artistic individualism and other principles of [[Art Nouveau]]. The theoretical declarations of the art movements were stated in Diaghilev's articles \"Difficult Questions\", \"Our Imaginary Degradation\", \"Permanent Struggle\", \"In Search of Beauty\", and \"The Fundamentals of Artistic Appreciation\" published in the N1/2 and N3/4 of the new journal.\n\n==Classical period==\n[[File:Mir.iskusstwa.1899.jpg|thumb|''Mir iskusstwa'' cover 1899 by [[Maria Yakunchikova]]]]\nIn its \"classical period\" (1898-1904) the art group organized six exhibitions: 1899 (International), 1900, 1901 (At the [[Imperial Academy of Arts]], Saint Petersburg), 1902 ([[Moscow]] and Saint Petersburg), 1903, 1906 (Saint Petersburg). The sixth exhibition was seen as a Diaghilev's attempt to prevent the separation from the Moscow members of the group who organized a separate \"Exhibition of 36 artists\" (1901) and later \"The Union of Russian Artists\" group (from 1903).<ref name=Pyman>{{cite book|last=Pyman|first=Avril|title=A History of Russian Symbolism|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0521241987|pages=121|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fF4pwE4LAygC&pg=PA121&dq=Mir+iskusstva+exhibitions&hl=cs&sa=X&ei=GtRfT_H0HcSVOqXblf4H&ved=0CFEQuwUwBA#v=onepage&q=Mir%20iskusstva%20exhibitions&f=false}}</ref> The magazine ended in 1904.<ref name=Pyman/>\n\nIn 1904-1910, ''Mir iskusstva'' did not exist as a separate artistic group. Its place was inherited by the Union of Russian Artists which continued officially until 1910 and unofficially until 1924. The Union included painters ([[Valentin Serov]], [[Konstantin Korovin]], [[Boris Kustodiev]], [[Zinaida Serebriakova]], [[Sergei Lednev-Schukin]]), illustrators ([[Ivan Bilibin]], [[Konstantin Somov]], [[Dmitry Mitrohin]]), restorators ([[Igor Grabar]]), and scenic designers ([[Nicholas Roerich]], [[Serge Sudeikin]]).\n\nIn 1910 Benois published a critical article in the magazine ''Rech'''  about the Union of Russian Artists. ''Mir iskusstva'' was recreated. [[Nicholas Roerich]] became the new chairman. The group admitted new members including [[Nathan Altman]], [[Vladimir Tatlin]], and [[Martiros Saryan]]. Some said that the inclusion of [[Russian avant-garde]] painters demonstrated that the group had become an exhibition organization rather than an art movement.  In 1917 the chairman of the group became [[Ivan Bilibin]].  The same year most members of the [[Jack of Diamonds (artists)|Jack of Diamonds]] entered the group.\n\nThe group organized numerous exhibitions: 1911, 1912, 1913, 1915, 1916, 1917, 1918, 1921, 1922 Saint-Petersburg, Moscow). The last exhibition of ''Mir iskusstva'' was organized in [[Paris]] in 1927. Some members of the group entered the ''[[Zhar-Tsvet]]'' (Moscow, organized in 1924) and ''[[Four Arts]]'' (Moscow-Leningrad, organized in 1925) artistic movements.\n\n==Art==\n[[Image:Dadon shemakha.jpg|thumb|right|Ivan Bilibin's illustration to ''[[The Tale of the Golden Cockerel]]''.]]\nLike the English [[Pre-Raphaelite]]s before them, Benois and his friends were disgusted with anti-aesthetic nature of modern [[industrial society]] and sought to consolidate all [[Neo-romanticism|Neo-Romantic]] Russian artists under the banner of fighting [[Positivism]] in art.\n\nLike the Romantics before them, the ''miriskusniki'' promoted understanding and conservation of the art of previous epochs, particularly traditional [[folk art]] and the 18th-century [[rococo]]. [[Antoine Watteau]] was probably the single artist whom they admired the most.\n\nSuch Revivalist projects were treated by the ''miriskusniki'' [[humor]]ously, in a spirit of self-[[parody]].  They were fascinated with [[mask]]s and [[marionette]]s, with [[Carnival|carnaval]] and [[puppet theater]], with [[dream]]s and [[fairy-tale]]s.  Everything [[grotesque]] and playful appealed to them more than the serious and emotional.  Their favorite city was [[Venice]], so much so that [[Diaghilev]] and [[Igor Stravinsky|Stravinsky]] selected it as the place of their burial.\n\nAs for media, the ''miriskusniki'' preferred the light, airy effects of [[watercolor painting|watercolor]] and [[gouache]] to full-scale oil paintings. Seeking to bring art into every house, they often designed [[Interior design|interiors]] and [[book]]s. Bakst and Benois revolutionized [[theatrical design]] with their ground-breaking decor for ''[[Cl\u00e9op\u00e2tre]]'' (1909), ''Carnaval'' (1910), ''[[Petrushka (ballet)|Petrushka]]'' (1911), and ''[[Afternoon of a Faun (Nijinsky)|L'apr\u00e8s-midi d'un faune]]'' (1912).\nApart from three founding fathers, active members of the ''World of Art'' included [[Mstislav Dobuzhinsky]], [[Eugene Lansere]], and [[Konstantin Somov]].  Exhibitions organized by the ''World of Art'' attracted many illustrious painters from Russia and abroad, notably [[Mikhail Vrubel]], [[Mikhail Nesterov]], and [[Isaac Levitan]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200px\" caption=\"Representative works\">\nFile:Bakst Uzhin.jpg|[[Leon Bakst]]\nFile:Dobuzhinsky City Types (City Grimaces) .jpg|[[Mstislav Dobuzhinsky]]\nFile:Nemetskaya.jpg|[[Alexandre Benois]]\nFile:Eliabeth lanceret.jpg|[[Eugene Lanceray]]\nFile:1911 Somov Liebesbrief anagoria.JPG|[[Konstantin Somov]]\n</gallery>\n\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\nHanna Chuchvaha, ''Art Periodical Culture in Late Imperial Russia (1898-1917). Print Modernism in Transition'' (Boston & Leiden: Brill, 2016) \n\n{{Russian art movements}}\n\n[[Category:1898 establishments in the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Russian symbolism]]\n", "n